Barrier Harmonic Dome: A Hybrid Active-Passive Shielding Architecture for Lunar Surface Habitats and Interplanetary Spacecraft

Ouadi Maakoul

March 2026

---

Abstract

Permanent human presence on the Moon and crewed missions to Mars require robust protection against space radiation—galactic cosmic rays (GCRs), solar energetic particles (SEPs), and solar wind plasma—as well as micrometeoroids and charged dust. The absence of a global magnetic field and atmosphere on the Moon makes its surface uniquely hazardous; interplanetary spacecraft face similar threats during long-duration transits. This dissertation develops and optimizes a hybrid active–passive shielding architecture, the Barrier Harmonic Dome (BHD), which combines a modular array of superconducting coils with in‑situ or carried passive shielding material. Two primary applications are addressed: lunar surface habitats and SpaceX Starship interplanetary missions.

The active component generates a tailored magnetic field via spherical harmonic synthesis using multiple REBCO coils, minimizing cusp leakage that plagues simple dipole shields. The passive component uses lunar regolith (on the Moon) or water (on Starship) to attenuate GCRs and remaining SEPs. A formal multi‑physics optimization framework couples Maxwell’s equations, magnetohydrodynamic and kinetic plasma descriptions, Boltzmann radiation transport, hypervelocity impact mechanics, and structural constraints. The objective is to minimize equivalent system mass while satisfying dose limits and engineering constraints.

For a lunar habitat of 50 m diameter, a 12‑coil array producing a 5 μT field reduces SEP leakage to below 10%, enabling a regolith thickness of 3–4 m for GCR protection, with total mass competitive with purely passive designs. For Starship, a 9 m diameter crew module, an 8‑coil array generating 20–150 μT reduces required water shielding from 4.2 m to 2.3 m, saving 27–29 tonnes (37–39%) compared to pure passive shielding. Variable‑field operation limits average cryogenic power to <1 kW for lunar habitats and <200 W for Starship. The modular, scalable architecture enables phased deployment aligned with near‑term space exploration roadmaps.

This work establishes the theoretical foundations, mathematical framework, and conceptual design for hybrid shielding, providing a basis for future high‑fidelity simulations and engineering development. The framework is general and can be adapted to other planetary surfaces or spacecraft.

