Chapter 1: The Lunar and Interplanetary Radiation Environment – Quantitative Threat Models

A rigorous shielding design must be based on quantitative descriptions of the hazards. This chapter provides the necessary environmental models, drawing on the latest observational data and reference spectra. The focus is on the physical parameters that directly influence shielding requirements: particle fluxes, energy spectra, and mechanical effects. Both lunar surface and interplanetary environments are considered.

1.1 Solar Wind Plasma

The solar wind is a continuous outflow of magnetized plasma from the Sun’s corona. At 1 AU, near the Moon’s orbit, its typical parameters are (Gombosi, 1998):

· Proton number density:  n \approx 5 \times 10^6 \ \mathrm{m^{-3}} 
· Velocity:  v \approx 4 \times 10^5 \ \mathrm{m/s} 
· Temperature:  T \approx 1 \times 10^5 \ \mathrm{K} 
· Interplanetary magnetic field strength:  B_{sw} \approx 5 \ \mathrm{nT} 

The dynamic pressure exerted by the solar wind is:

P_{sw} = n m_p v^2 \approx 1.34 \times 10^{-9} \ \mathrm{Pa}.

This pressure must be balanced by the magnetic pressure of any artificial shield to create a stand‑off cavity.

1.2 Solar Energetic Particles

Solar eruptions accelerate ions to high energies. SEP events are sporadic but can deliver lethal radiation doses within hours. For design purposes, we adopt the worst‑case spectrum from the February 1956 event (often used as a reference in lunar studies) and the October 1989 event (commonly used for interplanetary missions). The differential flux for protons is:

\frac{dJ}{dE} = C E^{-\gamma} \quad \text{for } E \text{ in MeV},

with \gamma \approx 3 for energies below 1 GeV. The integral fluence above 30 MeV can reach 10^{10} \ \mathrm{protons/cm^2} over several days.

1.3 Galactic Cosmic Rays

GCRs originate outside the solar system and consist of about 85% protons, 14% alpha particles, and 1% heavy ions (HZE). Their energy spectrum peaks around 1 GeV/nucleon. We use the Badhwar–O’Neill 2020 (BON2020) model (Slaba et al., 2020), which provides differential fluxes for all ions as a function of energy and solar modulation level. For conservative design, we assume solar minimum when GCR flux is highest.

1.4 Micrometeoroids

The lunar surface is bombarded by micrometeoroids with velocities 10–30 km/s. The mass flux follows the Grün distribution (Grün et al., 1985). For Starship in interplanetary space, the flux is similar. A 1 cm diameter particle (mass ≈ 1.4 g) at 20 km/s carries kinetic energy E_k \approx 2.8\times10^5 J, sufficient to penetrate thin walls.

1.5 Lunar Dust

Lunar regolith grains (1–100 μm) become electrostatically charged due to solar UV and plasma interactions, reaching potentials of ±10–100 V (Stubbs et al., 2006). Dust mitigation is essential for lunar surface systems.

1.6 Dose Limits

NASA’s space radiation exposure limits for a 1‑year mission are approximately 500 mSv for blood‑forming organs. A conservative design target of 50 mSv/year is adopted for this work, ensuring safety for multiple missions and providing margin.

