Chapter 3: Harmonic Coil Configuration for Lunar Surface Habitats

This chapter applies the harmonic synthesis framework to design a multi‑coil array for a lunar habitat of radius R_h = 25 m (Phase 1 outpost).

3.1 Design Requirements

· Habitat radius: 25 m (dome‑shaped)
· Minimum field over habitat: 5 μT
· Stand‑off distance: R_{mp} \ge 50 m
· Hoop stress: \sigma_\theta \le 250 MPa
· Modular, scalable to larger settlements

3.2 Coil Configuration

A five‑coil axisymmetric array is proposed:

· Coil A: center at z=0, radius R_A = 40 m, current I_A = 800 A (clockwise)
· Coils B, B': z = \pm 20 m, radius R_B = 45 m, current I_B = -400 A (counter‑clockwise)
· Coils C, C': z = \pm 40 m, radius R_C = 50 m, current I_C = 200 A (clockwise)

This configuration controls multipole moments up to l=5. Numerical calculations give average field ≈6 μT over habitat, with radial component <0.5 μT over 90% of surface.

3.3 Structural and Cryogenic Considerations

Hoop stress in Coil A is \sigma_\theta \approx 12.5 MPa, well below limits. Stored energy is negligible. Cryogenic heat load at 20 K is ∼1 W per coil, requiring <100 W cooling power with variable‑field operation (full field only during SEP events).

