Chapter 6: Multi‑Physics Optimization Framework

This chapter unifies the models into a formal optimization problem.

6.1 Design Variables

· Coil currents I_i for i = 1,\dots,N_c (continuous)
· Passive layer thickness x_p (continuous)
· Number of coils N_c (integer)

6.2 Objective: Equivalent System Mass

\mathrm{ESM} = M_{\mathrm{coils}} + M_{\mathrm{passive}} + \alpha P_{\mathrm{cryo}} + \beta P_{\mathrm{other}},

with \alpha = 100 kg/kW (power system specific mass), \beta similar, and masses computed from geometry and material densities.

6.3 Constraints

· Dose limit: D_{\mathrm{GCR}}(x_p) + \eta_{\mathrm{leak}}(\mathbf{I}) D_{\mathrm{SEP,0}}(x_p) \le 50 mSv/yr
· Stand‑off: R_{mp}(\mathbf{I}) \ge R_{\min} (e.g., 15 m for Starship, 50 m for lunar habitat)
· Hoop stress: \sigma_{\theta,i} \le 250 MPa
· Current limits: |I_i| \le I_{\max}

6.4 Solution Methodology

For fixed N_c, the problem reduces to a nonlinear program solvable by gradient‑based methods (e.g., SLSQP). Integer search over N_c yields the global optimum.

