Chapter 7: Engineering Implementation Challenges

This chapter addresses practical issues: cryogenics, dust mitigation, deployment, quench protection, and integration.

7.1 Cryogenic Power and Thermal Management

Heat loads include radiation (Q_{\mathrm{rad}} = A \sigma \epsilon (T_h^4 - T_c^4)) and conduction through supports. For a Starship coil (radius 7 m, surface area ∼4.4 m², \epsilon = 0.02):

Q_{\mathrm{rad}} \approx 4.4 \times 5.67\times10^{-8} \times 0.02 \times (300^4 - 20^4) \approx 40 \text{ W}.

Adding conduction, total per coil ∼41 W. For 8 coils, full‑field heat load ∼328 W. Cryocooler COP ∼0.015 gives electrical power ∼21.9 kW. With variable‑field operation (1.6% duty cycle), average power ∼350 W.

7.2 Dust Mitigation (Lunar)

Lunar dust is charged; electric fields from coil supports may attract it. Mitigation includes electrostatic shields, surface coatings, and strategic placement.

7.3 Deployment and Construction

Coils stow compactly and deploy via robotic arms or inflatable booms. Modular design allows phased expansion.

7.4 Quench Protection

Each coil requires quench detection and protection (e.g., quench heaters, dump resistors). Redundancy ensures safety.

