Chapter 8: Adaptation to Starship – Barrier Harmonic Dome for Interplanetary Transit

This chapter applies the BHD framework to SpaceX Starship, leveraging existing water tanks for passive shielding.

8.1 Starship Specifications

· Crew module diameter: 9 m, length: 20 m
· Water available: ∼5 tonnes baseline, additional capacity up to 20 tonnes
· Solar array power: 200–300 kW

8.2 Coil Architecture

Two main rings (radius 7 m) at z = \pm 10 m, plus four trim coils (radius 5 m) at intermediate positions, total 8 modules. Currents 500–2000 A per module, total dipole moment \sim 2.5\times10^7 A·m².

8.3 Plasma Leakage

For Starship, B_c \approx 15 μT from electron gyroradius scaling. With B_0 = 50 μT, \eta_{\mathrm{leak}} \approx 0.1 + 0.7/(1 + (50/15)^2) = 0.1 + 0.7/(1+11.1) = 0.1 + 0.7/12.1 \approx 0.16.

8.4 Optimization Results

Using the framework with a storm‑shelter radius 3 m, length 10 m, the optimal water thickness is 2.3 m (vs. 4.2 m pure passive). Mass breakdown:

Component Mass (tonnes)
Coils (conductor) 0.16
Support structure 0.8
Cryostat/insulation 0.4
Cryocoolers 0.2
Power electronics 0.1
Cabling/controls 0.2
Water (increment) 2–4
Water tanks/plumbing 0.5–1
Total 4.4–6.9

Average cryogenic power ∼350 W, peak 22 kW during SEP events.

8.5 Comparison with Pure Passive

Pure passive requires 4.2 m water → 74 tonnes for full cylindrical shell, or 79 tonnes for storm shelter. Hybrid saves 27–29 tonnes (37–39%).

