Appendix G: Elliptic Integrals and Special Functions

This appendix provides definitions and properties of special functions used in the dissertation.

G.1 Complete Elliptic Integrals

The complete elliptic integral of the first kind is:

K(k) = \int_0^{\pi/2} \frac{d\theta}{\sqrt{1 - k^2\sin^2\theta}}

The complete elliptic integral of the second kind is:

E(k) = \int_0^{\pi/2} \sqrt{1 - k^2\sin^2\theta} \, d\theta

Series expansions:

K(k) = \frac{\pi}{2} \left[ 1 + \left(\frac{1}{2}\right)^2 k^2 + \left(\frac{1\cdot 3}{2\cdot 4}\right)^2 k^4 + \cdots \right]

E(k) = \frac{\pi}{2} \left[ 1 - \left(\frac{1}{2}\right)^2 \frac{k^2}{1} - \left(\frac{1\cdot 3}{2\cdot 4}\right)^2 \frac{k^4}{3} - \cdots \right]

Limiting values:

K(0) = E(0) = \frac{\pi}{2},\quad K(1) \to \infty,\quad E(1) = 1

G.2 Modified Bessel Functions

Modified Bessel functions I_\nu(x) and K_\nu(x) appear in solutions to certain cylindrical problems. They satisfy:

x^2 \frac{d^2y}{dx^2} + x\frac{dy}{dx} - (x^2 + \nu^2)y = 0

Asymptotic forms:

I_\nu(x) \sim \frac{e^x}{\sqrt{2\pi x}} \quad (x \to \infty),\quad K_\nu(x) \sim \sqrt{\frac{\pi}{2x}} e^{-x} \quad (x \to \infty)

G.3 Gamma Function

The gamma function \Gamma(z) is defined for \Re(z) > 0 by:

\Gamma(z) = \int_0^\infty t^{z-1} e^{-t} \, dt

It satisfies \Gamma(z+1) = z\Gamma(z) and \Gamma(n+1) = n! for integer n.

